metadata.name: DisOrder #190
metadata.description:
Manual Dutch Auction (DA): 84 · 56 · 38 · 26 · 18  every 8 minutes.
Auction will stop changing price when non-reserves are fully minted.

/////////////////////////////////////////////////////

All that is, starts with Order.

Order attempts to evade entropy by following its own intrinsic patterns. Then, inevitably, there is change: an anomaly, a nudge that turns into a catalyst for widespread change.The momentum cannot be stopped.

Brief cycles build upon themselves, iterating and breaking into something new with each turn. Now, looking back, the accumulation of small divergences look like a leap, with trails of evolutionary decline casting tall shadows on the patterns that bore them.

The beauty of what this entropy creates, rises beyond chaos. It represents the past, and signals the future, and suddenly looks like a wild take on Order itself – the true DisOrder of life.

/////////////////////////////////////////////////////

metadata.name: Mythic Latent Glitches  #105
metadata.description:
What is even real and what is artificial?

In the contemporary light, the division between real and artificial loses weight as the concepts become more and more intertwined. In this work, the artist combines the human and generative inputs, in a counterintuitive manner, by allowing AI to design the organic elements and using the human hand to incorporate artificial glitches. What seemingly emerges as natural forms, was imagined solely by GAN, seeing the world through the limited examples through the photographer’s lenses. Artist’s role is also reversed, as their goal is to design the visual destruction process of the organic forms. Glitch is a malfunction of perception, it symbolizes the confusion caused by not being able to comprehend. 

The human fascination with metaphysical forces spans many centuries. While Pagan mythology created gods living in deep forests and under-explored territories, nowadays we approach technology with somewhat similar awe, fascination, and fear. 

The project has been developed in multiple stages. It started with an inspiration by the Lithuanian landscape and research of the ancient myths and legends. The photography aimed at capturing the mysterious, spanning months and years of different experiences. A custom pre-trained artist’s GAN model was then trained on a collection of several hundred photographs in high resolution. Selected outputs were curated by artist and included as a starting canvas for the next stage. Then, a set of stochastic manipulations were programmed to create alternative narratives through the visual destruction. Fog turns into smoke into burning radioactive forest in an unpredictable manner, guided by the random variables, their boundaries crafted by artist.  

Read more on the project website:
ivonatau.com/mythic-latent-glitches

- Use the "A" key to animate (if "Animated" feature is present).
- Press any key to stop the animation.
- Use the "S" key to export an image.

metadata.name: Magnolia Portrait #114
metadata.description:
Inspired by observation of the incessantly-rooted Pteridophyte and Magnolia, the cognominal series, “Magnolia”, portrays a manifestation of layers of constant streams crossing dynamically in a flow. Through years of growing in fluxed vapor, its knots and roots construct organized and rhythmic patterns within chaotic orders. From two-dimensional layouts to three-dimensional composition, “Magnolia” absorbs its fundamental image, and extend it even further — creating the core of generative artwork.

metadata.name: Limina #124
metadata.description:
Limina is a study of the fine line between order and chaos.

Each piece of the collection is made up of just one or two lines. These lines are defined by thousands of points that are chosen, one by one, by a simple algorithm moving across the canvas. What arises from that simple concept is a surprising variety of intricate patterns, accidental symmetries and traces of order in chaotic structures. 

Limina is a meditation on the concept of emergence, a concept that lies at the heart of generative art. The algorithm that defines the core of the series is only capable of making one simple choice: left, right, up or down? As it moves across the canvas, it leaves a trace of points that are connected by a curve. The order in which these points are chosen and the tightness of the curve connecting them is what creates the visual diversity of Limina. As these values fluctuate, symmetries emerge and break down again, forms, patterns and ornaments are created and combined to form both complex structures and simple abstractions. 

Limina shows the potential of minimalist generative concepts to generate visually dense and unexpected results. 

Press 's' to save your image.

metadata.name: Moving Blocks Mono #19
metadata.description:
Moving blocks formed by moving blocks.

How does it work?

Several shapes form boundaries. Within these boundaries, the moving blocks move pixels and rotate their color values from a specific color
to black.
Each shape has its own direction vector, which affects the feature-based directions and speed of the moving blocks.

Features:

- 109 colors: one from a unified color list (based on W3C SVG 1.0 color keyword names)
- 3, 5 or 7 shapes: 3 different sizes and 2 types (quads and circles)
- 1 - 3 clusters: shapes are assigned round-robin
- 10 rotation angles: from -168° to 168
- 5 grid sizes: based on Fibonacci numbers, starting with 377, block size is always 21
- Movable blocks: based on grid size (one Fibonacci number before)
- 127 directions of movement: based on 8 basic directions (up, up, left, left-up, left-down, right, right-up, right-down), limited to the 3,
  4, 8
  long combinations
- 2 behavior modes for movement distance: negative = decreasing and limited by range or shape, positive = increasing and limited by shape

Animation and feature selection are based on the deterministic prng XorShift128 seeded with the fxhash. This allows repeated playback in the
same order.

The size is fixed at 1980x1980 pixels.

The preview images are taken after 900 frames.

The animation will stop automatically at 900 frames. Press spacebar, click mouse or touch to change pausing. You can add `autopause` as
query string parameter to disable automatic pausing.

Press `c` to capture an image. Press `f` for fullscreen. Press `h` to see all options.

metadata.name: Zephyr #335
metadata.description:
The name Zephyr traces back to Zephyrus, the Greek god of the west wind, and refers to any light breeze. The flowing particles get pushed around by a zephyr, creating interesting and organic patterns.

- Default is 2000x2000 pixel canvas. Press “1” for 1000x1000px canvas, “3” for 3000x3000px, “4” for 4000x4000px
